section.label: Step 1 of 9: Select a Web service, port, and operation for the interaction

helpgrid.innerhtml: When you specify the URL for the WSDL file that defines the web service, the system validates the URL and updates the form with the WSDL definitions for ports and operations.
Select one port to use as the target for messages to the web service.

Select one operation that has the appropriate input and output elements for the interaction. Select the Process Response option if you want the web service to send response messages to the interaction for processing.

section.label: Step 2 of 10: Configure schema processing policies

helpgrid.innerhtml: Specify how the schema underlying the chosen web service should be processed; policies enable the appropriate processing of schema elements.

section.label: Step 2 of 9: Configure the request that will be sent from the application

helpgrid.innerhtml: The request hierarchy includes all the request parameters that are defined for the web service operation. To delete a request parameter, select that node, and click Remove Node.

Request Hierarchy displays the elements of the request that is associated with the selected Web service operation. Remove Node removes an element from the request, while Restore Node restores an element that you previously deleted. Clicking Reset will restore the initial request hierarchy.

Request Object Structure, Request Objects and Attributes will be created to enable a Web service request. Object Location Path on the object and attribute level will refer back to original Web service definition.

section.label: Step 3 of 9: Configure the response that will be sent back to the application

helpgrid.innerhtml: The response hierarchy includes all of the response parameters defined for the web service operation. To delete a response parameter not required for the interaction, select that node, and click Remove Node.

Response Hierarchy displays the elements of the response that are associated with the selected Web service operation. Remove Node removes an element from the response, while Restore Node restores an element that you previously deleted. Clicking Reset will restore the initial response hierarchy.

Response Object Structure, Response Objects and Attributes will be created to enable processing a Web service response. Object Location Path on the object and attribute level will refer back to original Web service definition.
Specify the application that initiates the interaction. Change the primary mapping object if you do not want to map the data from the main application object.

The application signature option (which is based on the interaction name) is used to authorize users to start the interaction from this application. The description for the signature option forms the action label if the interaction can be launched from the Select Action menu. The interaction mode controls what the user sees during the interaction, including both request and response, request or response only, or hiding the entire interaction from the user. Select Apply Response if you want the interaction to apply data from the response to the application. The Generate Dialog and Generate Menu Action options can be preset or read-only depending on the interaction mode that you select.

table.label: Application Security Groups Authorized To Launch Interaction

section.label: Step 5 of 9: Select and define the request fields

helpgrid.innerhtml: Specify which request fields will be shown when users launch the interaction, and which of those fields will be editable. The values that users enter in the fields will be sent to the Web service.

Clear the check box for any attribute that you do not want the user to see in the Request tab of the interaction window. You can change the field titles to be more intuitive, and you can set fields as read-only if you want to restrict the user from modifying a request before it is sent to the web service.

section.label: Step 6 of 9: Select and define the response fields

helpgrid.innerhtml: Specify which fields will be shown when the interaction receives a response from the Web service. You can mark fields as read-only to ensure that information from the Web service is not modified before being returned to the application.

Clear the check box for any attribute that you do not want the user to see in the Response tab of the interaction window. You can change the field titles to be more intuitive and you can set fields as read-only if you want to restrict the user from modifying a request before it is sent to the web service.

section.label: Step 7 of 9: Map information from the application to the Web service

helpgrid.innerhtml: If you map request objects and attributes to application objects and attributes, these values are inserted automatically when the user starts an interaction. You can manually configure mappings or, for more complex mappings, you can use a Java class and add this file to the application binding. You can use a combination of manual and Java class mapping techniques.

If you intend to use a Java class for mapping, enter the fully qualified name for the file in the Mapping Custom Class field. Use standard procedures to build and deploy the custom class so that it is available to the integration framework.

The application parent object is the same object that you set as the primary mapping object in step 4. Select Use Application Parent Object to map it to the request object. Alternatively, you can map to a related object by specifying its relationship to the application parent object. You can map multiple request objects to one or more application objects. After selecting a request object, click Select Request Attribute or New Row to map a request attribute to an application attribute.

section.label: Step 8 of 9: Map information from the Web service to the application

helpgrid.innerhtml: If you map response objects and attributes to application objects and attributes, the values are inserted automatically from the response from the web service. You can manually configure mappings or, for more complex mappings, you can use a Java class and add this file to the application binding. You can use a combination of manual and Java class mapping techniques.

If you intend to use a Java class for mapping, enter the fully qualified name for the file in the Mapping Custom Class field. Use standard procedures to build and deploy the custom class so that it is available to the integration framework.

The application parent object is the same object that you set as the primary mapping object in Step 4. Select Use Application Parent Object to map it to the response object. Alternatively, you can map to a related object by specifying its relationship to the application parent object. After selecting an application attribute, click Select Application Attribute or New Row to map an application attribute to a response attribute.

section.label: Step 9 of 9: Confirm creation of interaction

helpgrid.innerhtml: After you review and make any necessary changes, click Create to generate the artifacts for the interaction.
